**Selection Sort** is a simple, comparison-based sorting algorithm.
Its idea is to repeatedly select the smallest (or largest) element from the unsorted part of the list and place it in the correct position.

-> Given an array of size n:
-->Divide the array into two parts:
    Sorted part (initially empty)
    Unsorted part (initially the whole array)
--.For each position i from 0 to n-2:
    Assume the element at index i is the minimum
    Scan the remaining unsorted elements (i+1 to n-1)
    Find the actual minimum element
    Swap it with the element at index i
-->Repeat until the entire array is sorted.

# arr = [29,10,14,37,13]
arr = [10,13,14,29,37]

n = len(arr)
swap=0
for i in range(len(arr)-1):
    index = i
    for j in range(i+1,len(arr)):
        if arr[index]>arr[j]:
            index = j
            swap+=1
    arr[i],arr[index] = arr[index],arr[i]
    print('Step:{} --> {}'.format(i+1,arr))
    if swap==0:
        break

print(arr)

# Swap case is to decrease the Time Complexity when there are sorted arrays.

--> Key Characteristics
Time Complexity
  Best case: O(n²)
  Average case: O(n²)
  Worst case: O(n²)
Space Complexity
  O(1) (in-place sorting)
Stability
  ❌ Not stable (equal elements may change order)
Number of Swaps
  At most n-1 swaps (better than Bubble Sort)
--> Advantages and Disadvantages:
✅ Good for:
  Small datasets
  Learning and understanding sorting algorithms
  Situations where swap cost is high but comparisons are cheap
❌ Not suitable for:
  Large datasets
  Performance-critical applications.
